# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: passkeys-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] An **authenticator** is a means used to confirm a user's identity, that is, to perform digital authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A person authenticates to a computer system or application by demonstrating that he or she has possession and control of an authenticator.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] In the simplest case, the authenticator is a common password.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Using the terminology of the NIST Digital Identity Guidelines, the party to be authenticated is called the *claimant* while the party verifying the identity of the claimant is called the *verifier*.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] When the claimant successfully demonstrates possession and control of one or more authenticators to the verifier through an established authentication protocol, the verifier is able to infer the claimant's identity.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Authenticators may be characterized in terms of secrets, factors, and physical forms.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Every authenticator is associated with at least one secret that the claimant uses to demonstrate possession and control of the authenticator.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Since an attacker could use this secret to impersonate the user, an authenticator secret must be protected from theft or loss.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The type of secret is an important characteristic of the authenticator.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] There are three basic types of authenticator secret: a memorized secret and two types of cryptographic keys, either a symmetric key or a private key.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A memorized secret is intended to be memorized by the user.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A well-known example of a memorized secret is the common password, also called a passcode, a passphrase, or a personal identification number (PIN).
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] An authenticator secret known to both the claimant and the verifier is called a shared secret.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] For example, a memorized secret may or may not be shared.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A symmetric key is shared by definition.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] An important type of secret that is both memorized and shared is the password.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] In the special case of a password, the authenticator **is** the secret.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A cryptographic authenticator is one that uses a cryptographic key.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Depending on the key material, a cryptographic authenticator may use symmetric-key cryptography or public-key cryptography.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Both avoid memorized secrets, and in the case of public-key cryptography, there are no shared secrets as well, which is an important distinction.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Examples of cryptographic authenticators include OATH authenticators and FIDO authenticators.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The name OATH is an acronym from the words "Open AuTHentication" while FIDO stands for Fast IDentity Online.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Both are the results of an industry-wide collaboration to develop an open reference architecture using open standards to promote the adoption of strong authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] By way of counterexample, a password authenticator is **not** a cryptographic authenticator.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A symmetric key is a shared secret used to perform symmetric-key cryptography.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The claimant stores their copy of the shared key in a dedicated hardware-based authenticator or a software-based authenticator implemented on a smartphone.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The verifier holds a copy of the symmetric key.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A public-private key pair is used to perform public-key cryptography.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The public key is known to (and trusted by) the verifier while the corresponding private key is bound securely to the authenticator.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] In the case of a dedicated hardware-based authenticator, the private key never leaves the confines of the authenticator.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] An authenticator is something unique or distinctive to a user (*something that one has*), is activated by either a PIN (*something that one knows*), or is a biometric ("something that is unique to oneself").
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] An authenticator that provides only one of these factors is called a single-factor authenticator whereas a multi-factor authenticator incorporates two or more factors.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A multi-factor authenticator is one way to achieve multi-factor authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A combination of two or more single-factor authenticators is not a multi-factor authentication, yet may be suitable in certain conditions.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Authenticators may take a variety of physical forms (except for a memorized secret, which is intangible).
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] One can, for example, hold an authenticator in one's hand or wear one on the face, wrist, or finger.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] It is convenient to describe an authenticator in terms of its hardware and software components.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] An authenticator is hardware-based or software-based depending on whether the secret is stored in hardware or software, respectively.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] An important type of hardware-based authenticator is called a security key, also called a security token (not to be confused with access tokens, session tokens, or other types of security tokens).
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A security key stores its secret in hardware, which prevents the secret from being exported.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A security key is also resistant to malware since the secret is at no time accessible to software running on the host machine.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A software-based authenticator (sometimes called a software token) may be implemented on a general-purpose electronic device such as a laptop, a tablet computer, or a smartphone.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] For example, a software-based authenticator implemented as a mobile app on the claimant's smartphone is a type of phone-based authenticator.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] To prevent access to the secret, a software-based authenticator may use a processor's trusted execution environment or a Trusted Platform Module (TPM) on the client device.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A platform authenticator is built into a particular client device platform, that is, it is implemented on device.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] In contrast, a roaming authenticator is a cross-platform authenticator that is implemented off device.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A roaming authenticator connects to a device platform via a transport protocol such as USB.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The following sections describe narrow classes of authenticators.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] For a more comprehensive classification, see the NIST Digital Identity Guidelines.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] To use an authenticator, the claimant must explicitly indicate their intent to authenticate.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The latter is called a test of user presence (TUP).
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] To activate a single-factor authenticator (*something that one has*), the claimant may be required to perform a TUP, which avoids unintended operation of the authenticator.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A password is a secret that is intended to be memorized by the claimant and shared with the verifier.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Password authentication is the process whereby the claimant demonstrates knowledge of the password by transmitting it over the network to the verifier.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] If the transmitted password agrees with the previously shared secret, user authentication is successful.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] One-time passwords (OTPs) have been used since the 1980s.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] In 2004, an Open Authentication Reference Architecture for the secure generation of OTPs was announced at the annual RSA Conference.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The Initiative for Open Authentication (OATH) launched a year later.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Two IETF standards grew out of this work, the HMAC-based One-time Password (HOTP) algorithm and the Time-based One-time Password (TOTP) algorithm specified by RFC 4226 and RFC 6238, respectively.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] By OATH OTP, we mean either HOTP or TOTP.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] OATH certifies conformance with the HOTP and TOTP standards.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A traditional password (*something that one knows*) is often combined with a one-time password (*something that one has*) to provide two-factor authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Both the password and the OTP are transmitted over the network to the verifier.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] If the password agrees with the previously shared secret, and the verifier can confirm the value of the OTP, user authentication is successful.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] One-time passwords are generated on demand by a dedicated OATH OTP authenticator that encapsulates a secret that was previously shared with the verifier.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Using the authenticator, the claimant generates an OTP using a cryptographic method.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The verifier also generates an OTP using the same cryptographic method.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] If the two OTP values match, the verifier can conclude that the claimant possesses the shared secret.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A well-known example of an OATH authenticator is Google Authenticator, a phone-based authenticator that implements both HOTP and TOTP.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A mobile push authenticator is essentially a native app running on the claimant's mobile phone.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The app uses public-key cryptography to respond to push notifications.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] In other words, a mobile push authenticator is a single-factor cryptographic software authenticator.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A mobile push authenticator (*something that one has*) is usually combined with a password (*something that one knows*) to provide two-factor authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Unlike one-time passwords, mobile push does not require a shared secret beyond the password.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] After the claimant authenticates with a password, the verifier makes an out-of-band authentication request to a trusted third party that manages a public-key infrastructure on behalf of the verifier.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The trusted third party sends a push notification to the claimant's mobile phone.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The claimant demonstrates possession and control of the authenticator by pressing a button in the user interface, after which the authenticator responds with a digitally signed assertion.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The trusted third party verifies the signature on the assertion and returns an authentication response to the verifier.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The proprietary mobile push authentication protocol runs on an out-of-band secondary channel, which provides flexible deployment options.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Since the protocol requires an open network path to the claimant's mobile phone, if no such path is available (due to network issues, e.g.), the authentication process can not proceed.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A FIDO Universal 2nd Factor (U2F) authenticator (*something that one has*) is a single-factor cryptographic authenticator that is intended to be used in conjunction with an ordinary web password.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Since the authenticator relies on public-key cryptography, U2F does not require an additional shared secret beyond the password.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] To access a U2F authenticator, the claimant is required to perform a test of user presence (TUP), which helps prevent unauthorized access to the authenticator's functionality.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] In practice, a TUP consists of a simple button push.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A U2F authenticator interoperates with a conforming web user agent that implements the U2F JavaScript API.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A U2F authenticator necessarily implements the CTAP1/U2F protocol, one of the two protocols specified in the FIDO Client to Authenticator Protocol.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Unlike mobile push authentication, the U2F authentication protocol runs entirely on the front channel.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The first round trip is ordinary password authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] After the claimant authenticates with a password, the verifier sends a challenge to a conforming browser, which communicates with the U2F authenticator via a custom JavaScript API.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] After the claimant performs the TUP, the authenticator signs the challenge and returns the signed assertion to the verifier via the browser.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] To use a multi-factor authenticator, the claimant performs full user verification.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] To withdraw cash from an automated teller machine (ATM), a bank customer inserts an ATM card into a cash machine and types a Personal Identification Number (PIN).
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The input PIN is compared to the PIN stored on the card's chip.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] If the two match, the ATM withdrawal can proceed.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Note that an ATM withdrawal involves a memorized secret (i.e., a PIN) but the true value of the secret is not known to the ATM in advance.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The machine blindly passes the input PIN to the card, which compares the customer's input to the secret PIN stored on the card's chip.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] If the two match, the card reports success to the ATM and the transaction continues.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] An ATM card is an example of a multi-factor authenticator.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The card itself is *something that one has* while the PIN stored on the card's chip is presumably *something that one knows*.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Presenting the card to the ATM and demonstrating knowledge of the PIN is a kind of multi-factor authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Secure Shell (SSH) is a client-server protocol that uses public-key cryptography to create a secure channel over the network.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] In contrast to a traditional password, an SSH key is a cryptographic authenticator.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The primary authenticator secret is the SSH private key, which is used by the client to digitally sign a message.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The corresponding public key is used by the server to verify the message signature, which confirms that the claimant has possession and control of the private key.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] To avoid theft, the SSH private key (*something that one has*) may be encrypted using a passphrase (*something that one knows*).
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] To initiate a two-factor authentication process, the claimant supplies the passphrase to the client system.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Like a password, the SSH passphrase is a memorized secret but that is where the similarity ends.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Whereas a password is a shared secret that is transmitted over the network, the SSH passphrase is not shared, and moreover, use of the passphrase is strictly confined to the client system.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Authentication via SSH is an example of passwordless authentication since it avoids the transmission of a shared secret over the network.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] In fact, SSH authentication does not require a shared secret at all.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The FIDO U2F protocol standard became the starting point for the FIDO2 Project, a joint effort between the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) and the FIDO Alliance.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Project deliverables include the W3C Web Authentication (WebAuthn) standard and the FIDO Client to Authenticator Protocol (CTAP).
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Together WebAuthn and CTAP provide a strong authentication solution for the web.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A FIDO2 authenticator, also called a WebAuthn authenticator, uses public-key cryptography to interoperate with a WebAuthn client, that is, a conforming web user agent that implements the WebAuthn JavaScript API.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The authenticator may be a platform authenticator, a roaming authenticator, or some combination of the two.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] For example, a FIDO2 authenticator that implements the CTAP2 protocol is a roaming authenticator that communicates with a WebAuthn client via one or more of the following transport options: USB, near-field communication (NFC), or Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE).
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Concrete examples of FIDO2 platform authenticators include Windows Hello and the Android operating system.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] A FIDO2 authenticator may be used in either single-factor mode or multi-factor mode.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] In single-factor mode, the authenticator is activated by a simple test of user presence (e.g., a button push).
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] In multi-factor mode, the authenticator (*something that one has*) is activated by either a PIN (*something that one knows*) or a biometric ("something that is unique to oneself").
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] First and foremost, strong authentication begins with multi-factor authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The best thing one can do to protect a personal online account is to enable multi-factor authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] In practice, a common approach is to combine a password authenticator (*something that one knows*) with some other authenticator (*something that one has*) such as a cryptographic authenticator.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Generally speaking, a cryptographic authenticator is preferred over an authenticator that does not use cryptographic methods.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] All else being equal, a cryptographic authenticator that uses public-key cryptography is better than one that uses symmetric-key cryptography since the latter requires shared keys (which may be stolen or misused).
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Again all else being equal, a hardware-based authenticator is better than a software-based authenticator since the authenticator secret is presumably better protected in hardware.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] This preference is reflected in the NIST requirements outlined in the next section.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] NIST defines three levels of assurance with respect to authenticators.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The highest authenticator assurance level (AAL3) requires multi-factor authentication using either a multi-factor authenticator or an appropriate combination of single-factor authenticators.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] At AAL3, at least one of the authenticators must be a cryptographic hardware-based authenticator.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] See the NIST Digital Identity Guidelines for further discussion of authenticator assurance levels.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Like authenticator assurance levels, the notion of a restricted authenticator is a NIST concept.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] The term refers to an authenticator with a demonstrated inability to resist attacks, which puts the reliability of the authenticator in doubt.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Federal agencies mitigate the use a restricted authenticator by offering subscribers an alternative authenticator that is not restricted and by developing a migration plan in the event that a restricted authenticator is prohibited from use at some point in the future.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Currently, the use of the public switched telephone network is restricted by NIST.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] In particular, the out-of-band transmission of one-time passwords (OTPs) via recorded voice messages or SMS messages is restricted.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Moreover, if an agency chooses to use voice- or SMS-based OTPs, that agency must verify that the OTP is being transmitted to a phone and not an IP address since Voice over IP (VoIP) accounts are not routinely protected with multi-factor authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] It is convenient to use passwords as a basis for comparison since it is widely understood how to use a password.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] On computer systems, passwords have been used since at least the early 1960s.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] More generally, passwords have been used since ancient times.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] In 2012, Bonneau et al. evaluated two decades of proposals to replace passwords by systematically comparing web passwords to 35 competing authentication schemes in terms of their usability, deployability, and security.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] (The cited technical report is an extended version of the peer-reviewed paper by the same name.) They found that most schemes do better than passwords on security while *every* scheme does worse than passwords on deployability.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] In terms of usability, some schemes do better and some schemes do worse than passwords.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] Google used the evaluation framework of Bonneau et al. to compare security keys to passwords and one-time passwords.
[src:passkeys-deep/authenticator] They concluded that security keys are more usable and deployable than one-time passwords, and more secure than both passwords and one-time passwords.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] The **FIDO** (**Fast IDentity Online**) **Alliance** is an open industry association launched in February 2013 whose stated mission is to develop and promote authentication standards that "help reduce the world’s over-reliance on passwords".
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] FIDO addresses the lack of interoperability among devices that use strong authentication and reduces the problems users face creating and remembering multiple usernames and passwords.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] The USB security token device may be used to authenticate using a simple password (e.g. four-digit PIN) or by pressing a button.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] The specifications emphasize a device-centric model.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] Authentication over an insecure channel happens using public-key cryptography.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] The user's device registers the user to a server by registering a public key.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] To authenticate the user, the device signs a challenge from the server using the private key that it holds.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] The keys on the device are unlocked by a local user gesture such as a biometric or pressing a button.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] FIDO provides two types of user experiences depending on which protocol is used.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] Both protocols define a common interface at the client for whatever local authentication method the user exercises.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] The following open specifications may be obtained from the FIDO web site.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] The U2F 1.0 Proposed Standard (October 9, 2014) was the starting point for the specification known as FIDO 2.0 Proposed Standard (September 4, 2015).
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] The latter was formally submitted to the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) on November 12, 2015.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] Subsequently, the first Working Draft of the W3C Web Authentication (WebAuthn) standard was published on May 31, 2016.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] The WebAuthn standard has been revised numerous times since then, becoming a W3C Recommendation on March 4, 2019.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] Meanwhile the U2F 1.2 Proposed Standard (July 11, 2017) became the starting point for the Client to Authenticator Protocol 2.0 Proposed Standard, which was published on September 27, 2017.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] FIDO CTAP 2.0 complements W3C WebAuthn, both of which are in scope for the *FIDO2 Project*.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] The FIDO2 Project is a joint effort between the FIDO Alliance and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) whose goal is to create strong authentication for the web.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] At its core, FIDO2 consists of the W3C Web Authentication (WebAuthn) standard and the FIDO Client to Authenticator Protocol 2 (CTAP2).
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] FIDO2 is based upon previous work done by the FIDO Alliance, in particular the Universal 2nd Factor (U2F) authentication standard.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] Taken together, WebAuthn and CTAP specify a standard authentication protocol where the protocol endpoints consist of a user-controlled cryptographic authenticator (such as a smartphone or a hardware security key) and a WebAuthn Relying Party (also called a FIDO2 server).
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] A web user agent (i.e., a web browser) together with a WebAuthn client form an intermediary between the authenticator and the relying party.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] A single WebAuthn client Device may support multiple WebAuthn clients.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] For example, a laptop may support multiple clients, one for each conforming user agent running on the laptop.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] A conforming user agent implements the WebAuthn JavaScript API.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] As its name implies, the Client to Authenticator Protocol (CTAP) enables a conforming cryptographic authenticator to interoperate with a WebAuthn client.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] The CTAP specification refers to two protocol versions called CTAP1/U2F and CTAP2.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] An authenticator that implements one of these protocols is typically referred to as a U2F authenticator or a FIDO2 authenticator, respectively.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] A FIDO2 authenticator that also implements the CTAP1/U2F protocol is backward compatible with U2F.
[src:passkeys-deep/fido-alliance] The invention of using a smartphone as a cryptographic authenticator on a computer network is claimed in US patent 7,366,913 filed in 2002.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Usage of MFA has increased in recent years.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Security issues which can cause the bypass of MFA are fatigue attacks, phishing and SIM swapping.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Accounts with MFA enabled are significantly less likely to be compromised.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Authentication takes place when someone tries to log into a computer resource (such as a computer network, device, or application).
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] The resource requires the user to supply the identity by which the user is known to the resource, along with evidence of the authenticity of the user's claim to that identity.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Simple authentication requires only one such piece of evidence (factor), typically a password, or occasionally multiple pieces of evidence all of the same type, as with a credit card number and a card verification code (CVC).
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] For additional security, the resource may require more than one factor—multi-factor authentication, or two-factor authentication in cases where exactly two types of evidence are to be supplied.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] The use of multiple authentication factors to prove one's identity is based on the premise that an unauthorized actor is unlikely to be able to supply all of the factors required for access.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] If, in an authentication attempt, at least one of the components is missing or supplied incorrectly, the user's identity is not established with sufficient certainty and access to the asset (e.g., a building, or data) being protected by multi-factor authentication then remains blocked.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] An example of two-factor authentication is the withdrawing of money from an ATM; only the correct combination of a physically present bank card (something the user possesses) and a PIN (something the user knows) allows the transaction to be carried out.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Two other examples are to supplement a user-controlled password with a one-time password (OTP) or code generated or received by an authenticator (e.g. a security token or smartphone) that only the user possesses.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] An authenticator app enables two-factor authentication in a different way, by showing a randomly generated and constantly refreshing code, rather than sending an SMS or using another method.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] This code is a Time-based one-time password (a *TOTP*), and the authenticator app contains the key material that allows the generation of these codes.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Knowledge factors ("something only the user knows") are a form of authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] In this form, the user is required to prove knowledge of a secret in order to authenticate.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] A password is a secret word or string of characters that is used for user authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] This is the most commonly used mechanism of authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Many multi-factor authentication techniques rely on passwords as one factor of authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Variations include both longer ones formed from multiple words (a passphrase) and the shorter, purely numeric, PIN commonly used for ATM access.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Traditionally, passwords are expected to be memorized, but can also be written down on a hidden paper or text file.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Possession factors ("something only the user has") have been used for authentication for centuries, in the form of a key to a lock.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] The basic principle is that the key embodies a secret that is shared between the lock and the key, and the same principle underlies possession factor authentication in computer systems.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] A security token is an example of a possession factor.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] *soft token*) is a type of two-factor authentication security device that may be used to authorize the use of computer services.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] A soft token may not be a device the user interacts with.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Typically an X.509v3 certificate is loaded onto the device and stored securely to serve this purpose.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Inherent factors ("something the user is"), are factors associated with the user, and are usually biometric methods, including fingerprint, face, voice, or iris recognition.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Behavioral biometrics such as keystroke dynamics can also be used.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Increasingly, a fourth factor is coming into play involving the physical location of the user.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] While hard wired to the corporate network, a user could be allowed to login using only a pin code, whereas if the user was working remotely, a more secure MFA method such as entering a code from a soft token as well could be required.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Adapting the type of MFA method and frequency to a users' location will enable the avoidance of risks common to remote working.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Systems for network admission control work in similar ways where the level of network access can be contingent on the specific network a device is connected to, such as Wi-Fi vs wired connectivity.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] This also allows a user to move between offices and dynamically receive the same level of network access in each.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Two-factor authentication over text message was developed as early as 1996, when AT&T described a system for authorizing transactions based on an exchange of codes over two-way pagers.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Many multi-factor authentication vendors offer mobile phone-based authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Some methods include push-based authentication, QR code-based authentication, one-time password authentication (event-based and time-based), and SMS-based verification.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] SMS-based verification suffers from some security concerns.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Phones can be cloned, apps can run on several phones and cell-phone maintenance personnel can read SMS texts.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Not least, cell phones can be compromised in general, meaning the phone is no longer something only the user has.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] The major drawback of authentication including something the user possesses is that the user must carry around the physical token (the USB stick, the bank card, the key or similar), practically at all times.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Many organizations forbid carrying USB and electronic devices in or out of premises owing to malware and data theft risks, and most important machines do not have USB ports for the same reason.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Physical tokens usually do not scale, typically requiring a new token for each new account and system.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Procuring and subsequently replacing tokens of this kind involves costs.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] In addition, there are inherent conflicts and unavoidable trade-offs between usability and security.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Two-step authentication involving mobile phones and smartphones provides an alternative to dedicated physical devices.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] To authenticate, people can use their personal access codes to the device (i.e. something that only the individual user knows) plus a one-time-valid, dynamic passcode, typically consisting of 4 to 6 digits.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] The passcode can be sent to their mobile device by SMS or can be generated by a one-time passcode-generator app.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] In both cases, the advantage of using a mobile phone is that there is no need for an additional dedicated token, as users tend to carry their mobile devices around at all times.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Notwithstanding the popularity of SMS verification, security advocates have publicly criticized SMS verification, and in July 2016, a United States NIST draft guideline proposed deprecating it as a form of authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] A year later NIST reinstated SMS verification as a valid authentication channel in the finalized guideline.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] As early as 2011, Duo Security was offering push notifications for MFA via a mobile app.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] In 2016 and 2017 respectively, both Google and Apple started offering user two-step authentication with push notifications as an alternative method.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Security of SMS-delivered security tokens fully depends on the mobile operator's operational security and can be easily breached by wiretapping or SIM cloning by national security agencies.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] The Payment Card Industry (PCI) Data Security Standard, requirement 8.3, requires the use of MFA for all remote network access that originates from outside the network to a Card Data Environment (CDE).
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Beginning with PCI-DSS version 3.2, the use of MFA is required for all administrative access to the CDE, even if the user is within a trusted network.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] The second Payment Services Directive requires "strong customer authentication" on most electronic payments in the European Economic Area since September 14, 2019.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] In India, the Reserve Bank of India mandated two-factor authentication for all online transactions made using a debit or credit card using either a password or a one-time password sent over SMS.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] This requirement was removed in 2016 for transactions up to ₹2,000 after opting-in with the issuing bank.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Vendors such as Uber have been mandated by the bank to amend their payment processing systems in compliance with this two-factor authentication rollout.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Details for authentication for federal employees and contractors in the U.S. are defined in Homeland Security Presidential Directive 12 (HSPD-12).
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] IT regulatory standards for access to federal government systems require the use of multi-factor authentication to access sensitive IT resources, for example when logging on to network devices to perform administrative tasks and when accessing any computer using a privileged login.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] NIST Special Publication 800-63-3 discusses various forms of two-factor authentication and provides guidance on using them in business processes requiring different levels of assurance.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] In response to the publication, numerous authentication vendors began improperly promoting challenge-questions, secret images, and other knowledge-based methods as "multi-factor" authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Considering the reliability of the method, in some countries, MFA is obligatory in certain industries, such as healthcare, to prevent the theft of sensitive information.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] In the healthcare sector, the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Security Rule has historically listed access controls as a required implementation specification but did not explicitly mandate multi-factor authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] The HHS Office for Civil Rights noted in enforcement guidance that the lack of MFA was a contributing factor in multiple healthcare data breaches investigated under HIPAA.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] In December 2024, HHS published a Notice of Proposed Rulemaking that would make multi-factor authentication a mandatory requirement for all HIPAA-regulated entities accessing electronic protected health information.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] According to proponents, multi-factor authentication could drastically reduce the incidence of online identity theft and other online fraud, because the victim's password would no longer be enough to give a thief permanent access to their information.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] However, many multi-factor authentication approaches remain vulnerable to phishing, man-in-the-browser, and man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] To counter phishing attacks, users should not share their verification codes with anyone, and many web application providers will place an advisory in an e-mail or SMS containing a code.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] In May 2017, O2 Telefónica, a German mobile service provider, confirmed that cybercriminals had exploited SS7 vulnerabilities to bypass SMS based two-step authentication to do unauthorized withdrawals from users' bank accounts.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] The criminals first infected the account holder's computers in an attempt to steal their bank account credentials and phone numbers.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Then the attackers purchased access to a fake telecom provider and set up a redirect for the victim's phone number to a handset controlled by them.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Finally, the attackers logged into victims' online bank accounts and requested for the money on the accounts to be withdrawn to accounts owned by the criminals.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] SMS passcodes were routed to phone numbers controlled by the attackers and the criminals transferred the money out.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] An increasingly common approach to defeating MFA is to bombard the user with many requests to accept a log-in, until the user eventually succumbs to the volume of requests and by mistake accepts one.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] This form of social engineering is called *multi-factor authentication fatigue attack* (also MFA fatigue attack or MFA bombing), and may include other elements, such as calls pretending to be from IT support.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] When MFA applications are configured to send push notifications to end users, an attacker can send a flood of login attempts in the hope that a user will click on accept at least once.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] In 2022, Microsoft deployed a mitigation against MFA fatigue attacks with their authenticator app, by optionally requiring the user to type in a number in addition to clicking "approve".
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] In September 2022 Uber security was breached by a member of Lapsus$ using a multi-factor fatigue attack.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] In early 2024, a small percentage of Apple consumers experienced a MFA fatigue attack that was caused by a hacker that bypassed the rate limit and Captcha on Apple’s “Forgot Password” page.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Many multi-factor authentication products require users to deploy client software to make multi-factor authentication systems work.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Some vendors have created separate installation packages for network login, Web access credentials, and VPN connection credentials.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] For such products, there may be four or five different software packages to push down to the client PC in order to make use of the token or smart card.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] This translates to four or five packages on which version control has to be performed, and four or five packages to check for conflicts with business applications.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] If access can be operated using web pages, it is possible to limit the overheads outlined above to a single application.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] With other multi-factor authentication technology such as hardware token products, no software must be installed by end-users.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Some studies have shown that poorly implemented MFA recovery procedures can introduce new vulnerabilities that attackers may exploit.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] There are drawbacks to multi-factor authentication that are keeping many approaches from becoming widespread.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Some users have difficulty keeping track of a hardware token or USB plug.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Many users do not have the technical skills needed to install a client-side software certificate by themselves.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Generally, multi-factor solutions require additional investment for implementation and costs for maintenance.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Most hardware token-based systems are proprietary, and some vendors charge an annual fee per user.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Deployment of hardware tokens is logistically challenging.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Hardware tokens may get damaged or lost, and issuance of tokens in large industries such as banking or even within large enterprises needs to be managed.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] In addition to deployment costs, multi-factor authentication often carries significant additional support costs.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] A 2008 survey of over 120 U.S. credit unions by the *Credit Union Journal* reported on the support costs associated with two-factor authentication.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] In their report, software certificates and software toolbar approaches were reported to have the highest support costs.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] Research into deployments of multi-factor authentication schemes has shown that one of the elements that tend to impact the adoption of such systems is the line of business of the organization that deploys the multi-factor authentication system.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] While the perception is that multi-factor authentication is within the realm of perfect security, Roger Grimes writes that if not properly implemented and configured, multi-factor authentication can in fact be easily defeated.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] In 2013, Kim Dotcom claimed to have invented two-factor authentication in a 2000 patent, and briefly threatened to sue all the major web services.
[src:passkeys-deep/multi-factor-authentication] However, the European Patent Office revoked his patent in light of an earlier 1998 U.S. patent held by AT&T.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:passkeys-deep/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] While initially developed by Google and Yubico, with contribution from NXP Semiconductors, the standard is now hosted by the FIDO Alliance.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] While time-based one-time password (TOTPs) (e.g.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] 6-digit codes generated on Google Authenticator) were a significant improvement over SMS-based security codes, a number of security vulnerabilities were still possible to exploit, which U2F sought to improve.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] In terms of disadvantages, one significant difference and potential drawback to be considered regarding hardware-based U2F solutions is that unlike with TOTP shared-secret methods, there is no possibility of "backing up" recovery codes or shared secrets.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] If a hardware duplicate or alternative hardware key is not kept and the original U2F hardware key is lost, no recovery of the key is possible (because the private key exists only in hardware).
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] Therefore, for services that do not provide any alternative account recovery method, the use of U2F should be carefully considered.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] The USB devices communicate with the host computer using the human interface device (HID) protocol, the same protocol used by mice, keyboards, and other input devices.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] This avoids the need for the user to install special hardware driver software in the host computer and permits application software (such as a browser) to directly access the security features of the device without user effort other than possessing and inserting the device.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] Once communication is established, the application exercises a challenge–response authentication with the device using public-key cryptography methods and a secret unique device key manufactured into the device.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] The device key is vulnerable to malicious manufacturer duplication.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] In 2020, independent security researchers found a method to extract private keys from Google Titan Key, a popular U2F hardware security token.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] The method required physical access to the key for several hours, several thousand euros-worth of equipment, and was destructive to the plastic case of the key.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] The attackers concluded that the difficulty of the attack meant that people were still safer to use the keys than not.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] The attack was possible due to a vulnerability in the A700X microchip made by NXP Semiconductors, which is also used in security tokens made by Feitian and Yubico, meaning that those tokens are also vulnerable.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] The vulnerability was responsibly disclosed to the affected manufacturers so that it might be fixed in future products.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] U2F security keys are supported by Google Chrome since version 38, Firefox since version 57 and Opera since version 40.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] U2F security keys can be used as an additional method of two-step verification on online services that support the U2F protocol, including Google, Azure, Dropbox, GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket, Nextcloud, Facebook, and others.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] Chrome, Firefox, and Opera were, as of 2015, the only browsers supporting U2F natively.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] Microsoft has enabled FIDO 2.0 support for Windows 10's Windows Hello login platform.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] Microsoft Edge browser gained support for U2F in the October 2018 Windows Update.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] Microsoft accounts, including Office 365, OneDrive, and other Microsoft services, do not yet have U2F support.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] Mozilla has integrated it into Firefox 57, and enabled it by default in Firefox 60 and Thunderbird 60.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] Microsoft Edge starting from build 17723 support FIDO2.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] As of iOS and iPadOS 13.3 Apple now supports U2F in the Safari browser on those platforms.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] Additional specification documents may be obtained from the FIDO web site.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] The U2F 1.0 Proposed Standard (October 9, 2014) was the starting point for a short-lived specification known as the FIDO 2.0 Proposed Standard (September 4, 2015).
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] Meanwhile the U2F 1.2 Proposed Standard (April 11, 2017) became the starting point for the Client to Authenticator Protocol (CTAP) Proposed Standard, which was published on September 27, 2017.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] FIDO CTAP complements W3C WebAuthn, both of which are in scope for the FIDO2 Project.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] WebAuthn and CTAP provide a complete replacement for U2F, which has been renamed "CTAP1" in the latest version of the FIDO2 standard.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] The WebAuthn protocol is backward-compatible (via the AppID extension) with U2F-only security keys but the U2F protocol is not compatible with a WebAuthn-only authenticator.
[src:passkeys-deep/universal-2nd-factor] Some authenticators support both U2F and WebAuthn while some WebAuthn clients support keys created via the legacy U2F API.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] To use WebAuthn, users require a compatible authenticator.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] The standard does not specify how to store the keys required for signing, so a variety of authenticator types can be used.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] The most common authenticator type is a platform authenticator, which is built into the operating system of the device.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Common platform authenticators include Android, Apple Keychain and Windows Hello.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] These make use of hardware security features (such as TEE and TPM), and often sync credentials between devices for ease-of-use.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Another common authenticator type is a roaming authenticator, where a separate hardware device authenticates the user by connecting over USB, Bluetooth Low Energy, or near-field communications (NFC).
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Most smartphones can be used as roaming authenticators, and dedicated physical security keys are also used.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] WebAuthn is effectively backward compatible with FIDO Universal 2nd Factor (U2F) as they both use the CTAP protocol.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Password managers can also be used as an authenticator, often with cloud sync.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Where credentials sync is not viable or possible, WebAuthn Hybrid Transport can be used to access credentials stored on another authenticator such as a smartphone.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Like legacy U2F, WebAuthn is resistant to some phishing attacks as the authenticator only offers credentials that were registered on the same website.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] However, unlike U2F, WebAuthn can be implemented in a passwordless manner.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Moreover, a roaming hardware authenticator resists malware, since the keys are stored on a separate device, which prevents the malware from accessing them directly.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] The WebAuthn Level 1 and 2 standards were published as W3C Recommendations on 4 March 2019 and 8 April 2021 respectively.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] A Level 3 specification is currently a *First Public Working Draft* (FPWD).
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] WebAuthn is a core component of the FIDO2 Project under the guidance of the FIDO Alliance.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] FIDO2 is the successor to FIDO Universal 2nd Factor (U2F).
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Whereas U2F only supports multi-factor mode, having been designed to strengthen existing username/password-based login flows, FIDO2 adds support for single-factor mode.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] In multi-factor mode, the authenticator is activated by a test of *user presence*, which usually consists of a simple button push; no password is required.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] In single-factor mode, the authenticator (*something you have*) performs *user verification*.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Regardless of mode, the authenticator never shares its secrets or biometric data with the website.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Moreover, a single user's secret or biometric works with all websites, as the authenticator selects the correct cryptographic key material to use for the service requesting authentication after user verification was completed successfully.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] A secret and biometric on the authenticator can be used together, similarly to how they would be used on a smartphone.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] For example, a fingerprint provides convenient access to user's smartphone, but occasionally fingerprint access fails, in which case user can use a PIN.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] When Apple first introduced passkeys to the public in 2022, they emphasized their first-party platform integrations.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] This, combined with the lack of clear communication from other industry leaders, led some to speculate that passkeys were proprietary to Apple, which was not the case.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] As browsers and websites began to implement WebAuthn, the inconsistent feature-sets resulted in a variety of understandings of what exactly counted as a passkey.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Some people assumed that a passkey required management by a platform authenticator, or needed synchronization using the cloud.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] A better definition is that a passkey is any WebAuthn credential managed by any WebAuthn authenticator.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] This definition covers most of what different vendors refer to and accept as *passkeys*.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] WebAuthn specifies how a claimant demonstrates possession and control of a FIDO2 authenticator to a verifier called the WebAuthn Relying Party.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] The authentication process is mediated by an entity called the WebAuthn Client, which is little more than a conforming web browser.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Authenticator is a multi-factor cryptographic authenticator that uses public-key cryptography to sign an authentication assertion targeted at the WebAuthn Relying Party.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Assuming the authenticator uses either a facial recognition, fingerprint or PIN for user verification, the authenticator itself is *something you have* while the facial recognition and fingerprint (biometric) are *something you are* and the PIN is *something you know*.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] To initiate the WebAuthn authentication flow, the WebAuthn Relying Party indicates its intentions to the WebAuthn Client (i.e., the browser) via JavaScript.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] The WebAuthn Client communicates with the authenticator using a JavaScript API implemented in the browser.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] A roaming authenticator conforms to the FIDO Client to Authenticator Protocol (CTAP), and connected over USB, Bluetooth Low Energy, or near-field communications (NFC).
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] WebAuthn does not strictly require a roaming hardware authenticator.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Alternatively, a software authenticator (e.g., implemented on a smartphone) or a platform authenticator (i.e., an authenticator implemented directly on the WebAuthn Client Device) may be used.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Relevant examples of platform authenticators include Windows Hello and the Android operating system.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] WebAuthn Hybrid Transport allows the WebAuthn Client to access credentials stored on another authenticator such as a smartphone, useful in certain situations where credential sync is not viable.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] There is a lingering misunderstanding among users that biometric data is transmitted over the network in the same manner as passwords, which is not the case.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] When the WebAuthn Relying Party receives the signed authentication assertion from the browser, the digital signature on the assertion is verified using a trusted public key for the user.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] To obtain a public key for the user, the WebAuthn Relying Party initiates a WebAuthn registration flow that is similar to the authentication flow illustrated above.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] The primary difference is that the authenticator now signs an attestation statement with its attestation private key.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] The signed attestation statement contains a copy of the public key that the WebAuthn Relying Party ultimately uses to verify a signed authentication assertion.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] The attestation certificate contains metadata describing the authenticator itself.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] The digital signature on the attestation statement is verified with the trusted attestation public key for that particular model of authenticator.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] How the WebAuthn Relying Party obtains its store of trusted attestation public keys is unspecified.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] One option is to use the FIDO metadata service.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] The attestation type specified in the JavaScript determines the trust model.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] For instance, an attestation type called self-attestation may be desired, for which the trust model is essentially trust on first use.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] The WebAuthn Level 1 standard was published as a W3C Recommendation by the Web Authentication Working Group on 4 March 2019.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] WebAuthn is supported by Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Apple Safari and Opera.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] The desktop version of Google Chrome has supported WebAuthn since version 67.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Firefox, which had not fully supported the previous FIDO U2F standard, included and enabled WebAuthn in Firefox version 60, released on 9 May 2018.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] An early Windows Insider release of Microsoft Edge (Build 17682) implemented a version of WebAuthn that works with both Windows Hello as well as external security keys.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Existing FIDO U2F security keys are largely compatible with the WebAuthn standard, though WebAuthn added the ability to reference a unique per-account "user handle" identifier, which older authenticators are unable to store.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] One of the first FIDO2-compatible authenticators was the second-generation Security Key by Yubico, announced on 10 April 2018.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] The first FIDO2-compatible authenticators with a display was Trezor Model T by SatoshiLabs, announced on 6 November 2019.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Trezor Model T was also the first authenticator that allowed users to select which FIDO2 resident credential should be used directly on a device.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] The first Security Level 2 certified FIDO2 key, called "Goldengate" was announced one year later by eWBM on 8 April 2019.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Dropbox announced support for WebAuthn logins (as a 2nd factor) on 8 May 2018.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Apple announced that Face ID or Touch ID could be used as a WebAuthn platform authenticator with Safari on 24 June 2020.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Several password managers such as Bitwarden and Dashlane support WebAuthn.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] WebAuthn implements an extension of the W3C's more general Credential Management API, which is an attempt to formalize the interaction between websites and web browsers when exchanging user credentials.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] The Web Authentication API extends the Credential Management `navigator.credentials.create()` and `navigator.credentials.get()` JavaScript methods so they accept a `publicKey` parameter.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] To check if a browser supports WebAuthn, scripts should check if the `window.PublicKeyCredential` interface is defined.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] In addition to `PublicKeyCredential`, the standard also defines the `AuthenticatorResponse`, `AuthenticatorAttestationResponse`, and `AuthenticatorAssertionResponse` interfaces in addition to a variety of dictionaries and other datatypes.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] The API does not allow direct access to or manipulation of private keys, beyond requesting their initial creation.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] In August 2018, Paragon Initiative Enterprises conducted a security audit of the WebAuthn standard.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] While they could not find any specific exploits, they revealed some serious weaknesses in the way the underlying cryptography is used and mandated by the standard.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Paragon Initiative Enterprises also criticized how the standard was initially developed, as the proposal was not made public in advance and experienced cryptographers were not asked for suggestions and feedback.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Hence the standard was not subject to broad cryptographic research from the academic world.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Despite these shortcomings, Paragon Initiative Enterprises still encourage users to continue to use WebAuthn but have come up with some recommendations for potential implementers and developers of the standard that they hope can be implemented before the standard is finalized.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Avoiding such mistakes as early as possible would protect the industry from any challenges that are introduced by broken standards and the need for backwards compatibility.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] ECDAA was only designed to use in combination with device attestation.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] This particular feature of WebAuthn is not necessarily required for authentication to work.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Current implementations allow the user to decide whether an attestation statement is sent during the registration ceremony.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] Independently, relying parties can choose to require attestation or not.
[src:passkeys-deep/webauthn] ECDAA was removed from WebAuthn Level 2 as it was not implemented by browsers nor relying parties.
